<subSubSection id="C34F079DFFDEED41FF56FDFBFF5DFC9D" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BEA5416FFDEED41FF56FDFBFA91FDD1" blockId="2.[151,1437,452,2027]" box="[199,1325,596,622]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FF56FDFBFEF2FDD1" bold="true" box="[199,334,596,622]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named in reference to the fictional character Hunchback of Notre-Dame.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA5416FFDEED41FF56FDD7FF5DFC9D" blockId="2.[151,1437,452,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FF56FDD7FE11FD2D" bold="true" box="[199,429,632,658]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Generic placement.</emphasis>
. This species was placed in 
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDEED41FD70FDD7FCE7FD2D" authorityName="L. Koch" authorityYear="1872" box="[737,859,632,658]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FD70FDD7FCE7FD2D" box="[737,859,632,658]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Carepalxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because the females have two large cephalic humps. The male does not match the descriptions of the Australian 
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDEED41FCC3FD33FC70FD09" authorityName="L. Koch" authorityYear="1872" box="[850,972,668,694]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FCC3FD33FC70FD09" box="[850,972,668,694]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Carepalxis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males by the presence of the following characters: the unbranched second tibia (
<figureCitation id="136E4893FFDEED41FDFFFD6FFD7FFD65" box="[622,707,704,730]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–15" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,717,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-258@4.[163,1425,705,1915]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–15. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 11, Male left palp. 12–15, Male habitus (12, dorsal; 13, ventral; 14, frontal; 15, lateral). Voucher: 1–3, 6–8, (DZUB 9000); 4, 5, 9, 10, (DZUB 9274); 11–15, (DZUB 9284). Scale bars: genitalia, 0.25 mm; other drawings, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824329/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
), third and fourth coxae armed with macrosetae (
<figureCitation id="136E4893FFDEED41FA91FD6FFAE9FD65" box="[1280,1365,704,730]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–15" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,717,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-258@4.[163,1425,705,1915]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–15. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 11, Male left palp. 12–15, Male habitus (12, dorsal; 13, ventral; 14, frontal; 15, lateral). Voucher: 1–3, 6–8, (DZUB 9000); 4, 5, 9, 10, (DZUB 9274); 11–15, (DZUB 9284). Scale bars: genitalia, 0.25 mm; other drawings, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824329/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
), rodshaped paramedian apophysis connected to the conductor. This issue is discussed on the diagnostic notes section below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34F079DFFDEED41FF56FC83FC47FBD9" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BEA5416FFDEED41FF56FC83FC47FBD9" blockId="2.[151,1437,452,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FF56FC83FEFEFCF9" bold="true" box="[199,322,812,838]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDEED41FD0AFC83FCDAFCF9" authority="Simon" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1895" box="[667,870,812,838]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="camelus">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FD0AFC83FCABFCF9" box="[667,791,812,838]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. camelus</emphasis>
Simon
</taxonomicName>
due to the shape of the epigynum. Both share wide lateral plates and a hidden median plate in posterior view, moreover the scape is long and has a longitudinal groove. 
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDEED41FF06FCDBFE28FC31" authority="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta, 2022" authorityName="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta" authorityYear="2022" box="[151,404,884,910]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quasimodo" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FF06FCDBFE28FC31" box="[151,404,884,910]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Carepalxis quasimodo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FE0CFCDBFE61FC31" bold="true" box="[413,477,884,910]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A212357FFFDEED41FE0CFCDBFE61FC31" box="[413,477,884,910]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is different by having a larger scape and a narrower base. In ventral view, the scape has almost half the width of the base rather than one quarter (
<figureCitation id="136E4893FFDEED41FCAAFC37FC3CFC0D" box="[827,896,920,946]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[211,1372,217,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[203,1385,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 1–5, Epigynum (1, posterior; 1 ventral; 3, lateral; 4, ventral without scape; 5, posterior, cleared). 6–10, Female habitus; 6–8, female from Brasília (6, dorsal; 7, lateral; 8, frontal); 9–10, female from Jaborandi (9, dorsal; 10 lateral)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824326/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). The scape is slightly curved instead of straight. Additionally, the females lack the anterior median abdominal protuberance present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDEED41FBF1FC13FB61FC69" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1895" box="[1120,1245,956,982]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="camelus">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FBF1FC13FB61FC69" box="[1120,1245,956,982]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. camelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC429E7FFDEED41FB7DFC13FAD7FC69" author="Levi, H. W." box="[1260,1387,956,982]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" pagination="251 - 264" refId="ref6928" refString="Levi, H. W. (1992) The American species of the orb-weaver genus Carepalxis and the new genus Rubrepeira (Araneae: Araneidae). Psyche: A Journal of Entomology, 98 (2 - 3), 251 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.1155 / 1991 / 26493" type="journal article" year="1992">Levi, 1992</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 4). It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDEED41FEFAFC4FFD30FC45" authority="Petrunkevitch" authorityName="Petrunkevitch" box="[363,652,992,1018]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perpera">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FEFAFC4FFE5BFC45" box="[363,487,992,1018]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. perpera</emphasis>
Petrunkevitch
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDEED41FD56FC4FFC80FC45" authority="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta, 2022" authorityName="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta" authorityYear="2022" box="[711,828,992,1018]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="topazio" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FD56FC4FFC80FC45" box="[711,828,992,1018]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. topazio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FCD7FC4FFC3BFC45" bold="true" box="[838,903,992,1018]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A212357FFFDEED41FCD7FC4FFC3BFC45" box="[838,903,992,1018]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by having only one pair of tubercles (
<figureCitation id="136E4893FFDEED41FAD7FC4FFF4DFBA1" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[211,1372,217,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[203,1385,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 1–5, Epigynum (1, posterior; 1 ventral; 3, lateral; 4, ventral without scape; 5, posterior, cleared). 6–10, Female habitus; 6–8, female from Brasília (6, dorsal; 7, lateral; 8, frontal); 9–10, female from Jaborandi (9, dorsal; 10 lateral)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824326/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Figs. 6, 7, 9, 10</figureCitation>
. The posterior median plate is hidden, unlike those of similar 
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDEED41FC25FBABFB94FBA1" authority="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta, 2022" authorityName="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta" authorityYear="2022" box="[948,1064,1028,1054]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="topazio" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FC25FBABFB94FBA1" box="[948,1064,1028,1054]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. topazio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FBA0FBABFBCDFBA1" bold="true" box="[1073,1137,1028,1054]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A212357FFFDEED41FBA0FBABFBCDFBA1" box="[1073,1137,1028,1054]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="136E4893FFDEED41FB13FBABFB6BFBA1" box="[1154,1239,1028,1054]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–21" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[178,1417,449,1824]" captionTargetId="figure-78@5.[151,1435,417,1839]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 16–21. Carepalxis topazio n. sp. 16–18, Epigynum (16, ventral; 17, lateral; 18, posterior). 19–21, Female habitus (19, dorsal; 20, frontal; 21, lateral). Voucher: 16–21, (DZUB 8699). Scale bars: genitalia, 0.25 mm; other drawings, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824332" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824332/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
). The male is the first of this genus found in the Americas. It differs from the Australian 
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDEED41FC2CFB87FB7EFBFD" authority="Keyserling" authorityName="Keyserling" box="[957,1218,1064,1090]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcifera">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FC2CFB87FB83FBFD" box="[957,1087,1064,1090]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. furcifera</emphasis>
Keyserling
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDEED41FB6AFB87FEAEFBD9" authority="Keyserling" authorityName="Keyserling" authorityYear="1886" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FB6AFB87FA20FBFD" box="[1275,1436,1064,1090]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">C. tuberculata</emphasis>
Keyserling
</taxonomicName>
by the characters listed on the “generic placement” section above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34F079DFFDEED47FF56FBDFFD4CFE4A" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="393" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BEA5416FFDEED41FF56FBDFFC45F9E1" blockId="2.[151,1437,452,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FF56FBDFFEE5FB35" bold="true" box="[199,345,1136,1162]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FECCFBDFFBE0FB35" box="[349,1116,1136,1162]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
Female 
<typeStatus id="54EEEAB4FFDEED41FE27FBDFFDAAFB35" box="[438,534,1136,1162]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">holotype</typeStatus>
from Parque Ecológico Ermida Dom Bosco, Brasília
</emphasis>
. Total length 7.24. Carapace: 3.32 long, 2.98 wide, cephalic humps 1.90 high, thoracic region 1.09 high. Cephalic region brown, humps with dark top, thoracic region with light margin. Clypeus: 0.19. Chelicerae: brown, with a transversal dark stripe, fangs brown. Eyes: AME 0.12, ALE 0.06, PME 0.14, PLE 0.09. Eye interdistances: AME–AME 0.22, AME–ALE 0.52, PME–PME 0.29, PME–PLE 0.69, AME–PME 0.13. Endites: 0.79 long, 0.56 wide, brown, white from the half to median edges. Labium: 0.54 long, 0.69 wide, same color pattern as in endites. Sternum: 1.25 long, 1.41 wide, orange with numerous setae near to the first coxae. Legs: yellow with irregular brown rings and spots. Leg formula 1 2 4 3. Measures: L1. Femur 2.68, patella 1.15, tibia 2.05, metatarsus 1.97, tarsus 0.76 / L2. Femur 2.18, patella 0.90, tibia 1.73, metatarsus 1.96, tarsus 0.85 / L3. Femur 1.75, patella 0.93, tibia 1.13, metatarsus 0.95, tarsus 0.58/ L4. Femur 2.17, patella 1.11, tibia 1.53, metatarsus 1.86, tarsus 0.60 / Pedipalp. Femur 0.85, patella 0.53, tibia 0.61, tarsus 1.01. Abdomen: 6.11 long, 5.74 wide, 7.97 high. Grey with a big pair of anterior tubercles. Laterals with wavy black lines. Cardiac mark black, venter with a dark grey ellipse between epigynum and spinnerets. Epigynum with a long scape pointing to the spinnerets and wide lateral plates hiding the median plate. Spermathecae almost reaching the sides of the epigynum base; fertilization ducts in posterior half of the lateral plates.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA5416FFDEED47FF56F9C7FD1AFF46" blockId="2.[151,1437,452,2027]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,150,681]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="393" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDEED41FF56F9C7FCABF93D" box="[199,791,1640,1667]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
Male 
<typeStatus id="54EEEAB4FFDEED41FE9BF9C6FED2F93D" box="[266,366,1641,1666]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">paratype</typeStatus>
from Fazenda Trijunção, Jaborandi.
</emphasis>
Total length 5.28. Carapace: 2.93 long, 2.50 wide, 1.28 high. Cephalic region brown with a transverse light spot on top of slight elevations, thoracic region with dark sides and a black thoracic groove.A large seta is present near the PLE on each side. Clypeus: 0.23. Chelicerae: dark brown with brown fangs. Eye diameters: AME 0.13, ALE 0.09, PME 0.14, PLE 0.10. Eye interdistances: AME–AME 0.18, AME–ALE 0.46, PME–PME 0.28, PME–PLE 0.47, AME–PME 0.09. Endites: 0.39 long, 0.40 wide, colors as in females. Labium: 0.23 long, 0.44 wide, colors as in females. Sternum: 1.20 long, 1.02 wide, yellow with white spots. Legs: same colors as in females. All femora with a ventral row of large macrosetae. Second leg with highly modified, with a femoral groove, ventral row of thick and short spines and the tibia is armed with strong macrosetae. First coxae with a distal and retrolateral hook, third and fourth coxae and patella with a short macrosetae each, fourth femur with three proximal macrosetae. Leg formula 1 2 4 3. Measures: L1. Femur 3.04, patella 1.21, tibia 2.31, metatarsus 2.06, tarsus 0.87 / L2. Femur 2.75, patella 1.07, tibia 2.07, metatarsus 2.05, tarsus 0.83 / L3. Femur 1.47, patella 0.86, tibia 1.04, metatarsus 1.06, tarsus 0.50 / L4. Femur 2.22, patella 1.04, tibia 1.64, metatarsus 1.62, tarsus 0.63. Abdomen: 3.09 long, 2.43 wide, 1.63 high. Colors and features as in females, but no wavy black lines in the sides. The venter is uniformly grey.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF2A049EFFDFED40FF06F838FE60F847" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824326" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5824326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824326/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="392" startId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" targetBox="[211,1372,217,1901]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="8BEA5416FFDFED40FF06F838FE60F847" blockId="3.[151,1436,1943,2040]" pageId="3" pageNumber="392">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDFED40FF06F838FEF6F810" bold="true" box="[151,330,1943,1967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="392">FIGURES 1–10.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C552F95FFDFED40FEC5F837FD86F80F" authority="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta, 2022" authorityName="Ferreira-Sousa &amp; Motta" authorityYear="2022" box="[340,570,1944,1968]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Carepalxis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="392" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quasimodo" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDFED40FEC5F837FD86F80F" box="[340,570,1944,1968]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="392">Carepalxis quasimodo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9218804FFDFED40FDD5F837FD3CF80F" bold="true" box="[580,640,1944,1968]" pageId="3" pageNumber="392">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A212357FFFDFED40FDD5F837FD3CF80F" box="[580,640,1944,1968]" pageId="3" pageNumber="392" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
1–5, Epigynum (1, posterior; 1 ventral; 3, lateral; 4, ventral without scape; 5, posterior, cleared). 6–10, Female habitus; 6–8, female from Brasília (6, dorsal; 7, lateral; 8, frontal); 9–10, female from Jaborandi (9, dorsal; 10 lateral).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BEA5416FFD8ED47FF56FEADFEECFE36" blockId="4.[151,1437,150,681]" pageId="4" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFD8ED47FF56FEADFE83FEA3" bold="true" box="[199,319,258,284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="393">Variation.</emphasis>
Total length of females 7.9 to 9.0. The female from Brasilia has much higher tubercles (about 2.0) than the others from Jaborandi (about 0.7 high) (
<figureCitation id="136E4893FFD8ED47FD2AFE88FC9BFEFE" box="[699,807,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[211,1372,217,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[203,1385,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 1–5, Epigynum (1, posterior; 1 ventral; 3, lateral; 4, ventral without scape; 5, posterior, cleared). 6–10, Female habitus; 6–8, female from Brasília (6, dorsal; 7, lateral; 8, frontal); 9–10, female from Jaborandi (9, dorsal; 10 lateral)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824326/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="393">Figs. 6, 7</figureCitation>
). The cardiac mark might be black or white. Specimens from Jaborandi have a transversal light band on top of their cephalic humps (
<figureCitation id="136E4893FFD8ED47FC6FFEE4FBFFFEDA" box="[1022,1091,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[211,1372,217,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[203,1385,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 1–5, Epigynum (1, posterior; 1 ventral; 3, lateral; 4, ventral without scape; 5, posterior, cleared). 6–10, Female habitus; 6–8, female from Brasília (6, dorsal; 7, lateral; 8, frontal); 9–10, female from Jaborandi (9, dorsal; 10 lateral)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824326/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="393">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), in the male this band is even lighter (
<figureCitation id="136E4893FFD8ED47FF61FEC0FEFFFE36" box="[240,323,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–15" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1938,1962]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,717,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-258@4.[163,1425,705,1915]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–15. Carepalxis quasimodo n. sp. 11, Male left palp. 12–15, Male habitus (12, dorsal; 13, ventral; 14, frontal; 15, lateral). Voucher: 1–3, 6–8, (DZUB 9000); 4, 5, 9, 10, (DZUB 9274); 11–15, (DZUB 9284). Scale bars: genitalia, 0.25 mm; other drawings, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5824329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5824329/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="393">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA5416FFD8ED47FF56FE3DFD4CFE4A" blockId="4.[151,1437,150,681]" pageId="4" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFD8ED47FF56FE3DFE34FE12" bold="true" box="[199,392,402,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="393">Matching sexes.</emphasis>
The only known male and 
<specimenCount id="9D539F9FFFD8ED47FD5BFE3CFCF4FE12" box="[714,840,403,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="393" type="female">one female</specimenCount>
from Jaborandi were collected at night in the same tree. They are deemed to be conspecific based on the same colour pattern and similar modifications in the carapace, although the male cephalic elevation is much smaller.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34F079DFFD8ED47FF56FE51FD94FD16" pageId="4" pageNumber="393" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BEA5416FFD8ED47FF56FE51FD94FD16" blockId="4.[151,1437,150,681]" pageId="4" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis id="B9218804FFD8ED47FF56FE51FDECFDA7" bold="true" box="[199,592,510,537]" pageId="4" pageNumber="393">Distribution and natural history.</emphasis>
The females were hanging in the hub of complete orb-webs, the male was hanging in a single thread. All the specimens were collected in the early rainy season. In the laboratory, 
<specimenCount id="9D539F9FFFD8ED47FAB0FD8CFA20FD82" box="[1313,1436,547,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="393" type="female">one female</specimenCount>
from Jaborandi made an egg sac and wrapped it with the data label (similar to what it probably does to hide its eggs with leaves in nature). The spiderlings started to hatch after 17 days. This species occurs in Central 
<collectingCountry id="F3421486FFD8ED47FB67FDC4FA81FD3A" box="[1270,1341,619,645]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="393">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, in open vegetation from the Cerrado biome.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
